{"format":"tiptap/v1","doc":{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What NER Does"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Named Entity Recognition (NER)"},{"type":"text","text":" locates and classifies real-world entities mentioned in text — people, organisations, locations, dates, monetary values, and more. Unlike text classification (which assigns one label to the whole document), NER is a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"token-level"},{"type":"text","text":" task: every token in the sentence gets a label. NER is a foundational building block for information extraction, knowledge graph construction, and search."}]},{"type":"image","attrs":{"src":"data:image/svg+xml;base64,","alt":"NER tagging diagram showing 'Apple acquired Beats Electronics in 2014 for $3 billion' with BIO labels: B-ORG for Apple, B-ORG/I-ORG for Beats Electronics, B-DATE for 2014, B-MONEY/I-MONEY for $3 billion"}},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"The BIO Tagging Scheme"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"NER is modelled as a sequence labelling problem. Each token receives a tag in the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"BIO"},{"type":"text","text":" (Begin-Inside-Outside) format:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"B-TYPE"},{"type":"text","text":" — the first token of a named entity of the given type."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"I-TYPE"},{"type":"text","text":" — a continuation token inside the same entity (\"Beats Electronics\" → B-ORG, I-ORG)."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"O"},{"type":"text","text":" — not part of any entity."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Standard CoNLL-2003 entity types are "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"PER"},{"type":"text","text":" (person), "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"ORG"},{"type":"text","text":" (organisation), "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"LOC"},{"type":"text","text":" (location), and "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"MISC"},{"type":"text","text":". spaCy's models extend this to 18 types including "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"DATE"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"MONEY"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"GPE"},{"type":"text","text":" (geo-political entity), and "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"PRODUCT"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"NER with spaCy"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"spaCy ships pretrained pipelines that run NER as part of a full linguistic pipeline. The "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"en_core_web_trf"},{"type":"text","text":" model is transformer-based and most accurate; "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"en_core_web_sm"},{"type":"text","text":" is faster and CPU-friendly."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import spacy\n\n# pip install spacy && python -m spacy download en_core_web_sm\nnlp = spacy.load(\"en_core_web_sm\")\n\ntext = \"Apple acquired Beats Electronics in 2014 for $3 billion.\"\ndoc = nlp(text)\n\nfor ent in doc.ents:\n    print(f\"{ent.text!r:20} {ent.label_:10} {spacy.explain(ent.label_)}\")\n\n# 'Apple'             ORG        Companies, agencies, institutions...\n# 'Beats Electronics' ORG        Companies, agencies, institutions...\n# '2014'              DATE       Absolute or relative dates or periods\n# '$3 billion'        MONEY      Monetary values, including unit\n\n# Visualise in Jupyter:\nfrom spacy import displacy\ndisplacy.render(doc, style=\"ent\")"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"NER with Transformers (Hugging Face)"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"from transformers import pipeline\n\n# Uses dslim/bert-base-NER by default — fine-tuned on CoNLL-2003\nner = pipeline(\"ner\", aggregation_strategy=\"simple\")\n\nresults = ner(\"Apple acquired Beats Electronics in 2014 for $3 billion.\")\nfor r in results:\n    print(f\"{r['word']:20} {r['entity_group']:8} score={r['score']:.2f}\")\n\n# Apple                ORG      score=1.00\n# Beats Electronics    ORG      score=1.00\n# 2014                 MISC     score=0.75  ← DATE may not appear in CoNLL types\n\n# aggregation_strategy=\"simple\" merges B-/I- tokens into spans automatically"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For domain-specific entities (medical, legal, biomedical), use a model fine-tuned on in-domain data. Hugging Face Hub has hundreds: "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"d4data/biomedical-ner-all"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"nlpaueb/legal-bert-base-uncased"},{"type":"text","text":", etc."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Fine-tuning a NER Model"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"from datasets import load_dataset\nfrom transformers import (\n    AutoTokenizer,\n    AutoModelForTokenClassification,\n    TrainingArguments,\n    Trainer,\n    DataCollatorForTokenClassification,\n)\nimport numpy as np\nfrom seqeval.metrics import f1_score, classification_report\n\n# CoNLL-2003: tokens with PER, ORG, LOC, MISC labels in BIO format\ndataset = load_dataset(\"conll2003\")\nlabel_names = dataset[\"train\"].features[\"ner_tags\"].feature.names\n# ['O', 'B-PER', 'I-PER', 'B-ORG', 'I-ORG', 'B-LOC', 'I-LOC', 'B-MISC', 'I-MISC']\n\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"distilbert-base-uncased\")\n\ndef tokenize_and_align(example):\n    tokenized = tokenizer(example[\"tokens\"], truncation=True, is_split_into_words=True)\n    labels = []\n    for i, word_id in enumerate(tokenized.word_ids()):\n        if word_id is None:\n            labels.append(-100)  # special tokens — ignored in loss\n        else:\n            # Only label the first sub-token of each word\n            labels.append(example[\"ner_tags\"][word_id] if tokenized.word_ids()[i] != tokenized.word_ids()[i-1] or i == 0 else -100)\n    tokenized[\"labels\"] = labels\n    return tokenized\n\ntokenized_ds = dataset.map(tokenize_and_align, batched=False)\n\nmodel = AutoModelForTokenClassification.from_pretrained(\n    \"distilbert-base-uncased\",\n    num_labels=len(label_names),\n    id2label={i: l for i, l in enumerate(label_names)},\n    label2id={l: i for i, l in enumerate(label_names)},\n)\n\ntraining_args = TrainingArguments(\n    output_dir=\"./ner-distilbert\",\n    num_train_epochs=3,\n    per_device_train_batch_size=16,\n    evaluation_strategy=\"epoch\",\n    learning_rate=2e-5,\n)\n\ntrainer = Trainer(\n    model=model,\n    args=training_args,\n    train_dataset=tokenized_ds[\"train\"],\n    eval_dataset=tokenized_ds[\"validation\"],\n    data_collator=DataCollatorForTokenClassification(tokenizer),\n)\ntrainer.train()\n# Typical CoNLL-2003 F1: ~90-91 after 3 epochs"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Evaluating NER: Span-Level F1"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"NER is evaluated at the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"span level"},{"type":"text","text":", not the token level. A predicted entity is correct only if both its boundaries and its type match the gold annotation exactly. The "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"seqeval"},{"type":"text","text":" library handles this correctly."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"from seqeval.metrics import classification_report\n\ngold = [[\"B-ORG\", \"I-ORG\", \"O\", \"B-PER\"]]\npred = [[\"B-ORG\", \"I-ORG\", \"O\", \"B-ORG\"]]  # last token wrong type\n\nprint(classification_report(gold, pred))\n#           precision    recall  f1-score   support\n# ORG           0.50      1.00      0.67         1\n# PER           0.00      0.00      0.00         1\n# micro avg     0.50      0.50      0.50         2\n\n# 'Beats Electronics' (2-token span) counts as ONE entity:\n# both tokens must match for it to be a true positive."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Common Pitfalls"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sub-word tokenisation."},{"type":"text","text":" BERT splits \"Beats\" into [\"Beat\", \"##s\"]. Only label the first sub-token; set others to -100 so they don't contribute to the loss."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Domain mismatch."},{"type":"text","text":" A model trained on news text will miss medical drug names or legal citations. Fine-tune on in-domain examples or use a specialist model."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Ambiguous entities."},{"type":"text","text":" \"Apple\" is ORG in a tech context and not an entity in a recipe. Contextual transformer models handle this much better than rule-based systems."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Nested entities."},{"type":"text","text":" Standard BIO does not support nesting (\"[Bank of [America]]\"). Span-based models (SpanBERT) or the BIOES tagging scheme address this."}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Why NER Matters"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Named entity recognition is a linchpin of information extraction pipelines. Without it, unstructured text — news articles, clinical notes, legal contracts, support tickets — remains opaque to automated systems. NER is what converts raw language into structured, queryable data."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Consider a financial intelligence platform that ingests thousands of news articles per hour. Without NER, identifying which companies are mentioned alongside earnings figures requires expensive manual annotation. With NER, an automated pipeline can extract (company, financial-metric, value, date) tuples at scale and feed them directly into a knowledge graph or alert system."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"In clinical NLP, NER over discharge summaries extracts medications, dosages, diagnoses, and procedures — enabling cohort analysis, adverse event detection, and regulatory reporting that would otherwise require physician review. Clinical NER is so consequential that domain-adapted models (BioBERT, ClinicalBERT) have become standard, since general-domain models miss clinical abbreviations and drug names."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Benefits"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Structured extraction from free text."},{"type":"text","text":" NER converts unstructured prose into (entity, type) pairs that can be stored in databases, queried with SQL, and fed into downstream models."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Enables knowledge graph construction."},{"type":"text","text":" Relations between entities (\"Apple acquired Beats\") become graph edges only after entities are first identified."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Improves search and retrieval."},{"type":"text","text":" Entity-aware search (\"find articles mentioning Tesla as an ORG, not the inventor\") is only possible when entities are tagged."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Strong pre-trained models available."},{"type":"text","text":" spaCy, Hugging Face pipelines, and domain-specific BERT variants give you high-quality NER with a few lines of code, before any fine-tuning."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Multilingual coverage."},{"type":"text","text":" Models like mBERT and XLM-R generalise NER to 100+ languages from a single checkpoint."}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Trade-offs and Limitations"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Limitation"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Detail"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Domain mismatch"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"CoNLL-trained models drop 20–40 F1 points on biomedical or legal text"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"No nested entities in BIO"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Standard BIO cannot represent '[Bank of [America LOC] ORG]'; requires span-based models"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Span-level evaluation"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"A span is only a true positive if both boundary and type are correct — partial matches score zero"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sub-word tokenisation mismatch"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"BERT splits words into sub-tokens; only the first sub-token should carry the label"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Annotation cost"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"High-quality NER labels require expert annotators; clinical text annotation needs clinicians"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"How NER Works — Core Mechanics"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Modern NER is a token classification problem. Given a sequence of tokens "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"x_1, x_2, \\ldots, x_T"}},{"type":"text","text":", the model assigns a label "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"y_t \\in \\{\\text{B-PER}, \\text{I-PER}, \\ldots, \\text{O}\\}"}},{"type":"text","text":" to each token. A pretrained transformer encoder converts tokens to contextual embeddings; a linear head projects each embedding to label logits."}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"\\hat{y}_t = \\text{softmax}(W \\cdot h_t + b), \\quad h_t = \\text{Encoder}(x_1, \\ldots, x_T)_t"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Training minimises token-level cross-entropy, summed over all positions except padding (which uses the "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"-100"}},{"type":"text","text":" ignore-index convention):"}]},{"type":"blockMath","attrs":{"latex":"\\mathcal{L} = -\\sum_{t=1}^{T} \\mathbf{1}[y_t \\neq -100] \\log P(y_t \\mid x_1, \\ldots, x_T)"}},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The Conditional Random Field (CRF) output layer is a classic alternative that models label transitions explicitly. It adds a transition matrix "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"A \\in \\mathbb{R}^{|L| \\times |L|}"}},{"type":"text","text":" where "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"A_{ij}"}},{"type":"text","text":" is the score of transitioning from label "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"i"}},{"type":"text","text":" to label "},{"type":"inlineMath","attrs":{"latex":"j"}},{"type":"text","text":". The CRF prevents impossible sequences like I-PER following O without a B-PER. In the transformer era, the CRF improves F1 by 0.5–2 points on most benchmarks — a small but consistent gain."}]},{"type":"image","attrs":{"src":"data:image/svg+xml;base64,","alt":"NER pipeline architecture from raw text through tokenizer, encoder (BERT/BiLSTM), token classifier to BIO output and span assembly"}},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"When to Use NER"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Use NER when"},{"type":"text","text":" you need to extract structured entities from unstructured text at scale, build a knowledge graph, power entity-aware search, or feed structured data to a downstream pipeline (relation extraction, question answering, slot filling)."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Do not use NER when"},{"type":"text","text":" your information need is better served by document classification (no span-level signal needed), regular expressions (perfectly regular patterns like IP addresses, emails), or when you need to extract nested or overlapping entities — standard BIO NER cannot represent these and you need a span-based approach (SpanBERT, SuAIEE)."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Real-World Example — News Monitoring Pipeline"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The following shows a production-style pipeline that ingests news text, extracts entities, and aggregates company mentions with sentiment scores. This pattern is common in financial intelligence, media monitoring, and competitive analysis systems."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"from transformers import pipeline\nfrom collections import defaultdict\nimport json\n\n# Load NER pipeline once at startup (expensive model load)\nner = pipeline(\n    \"ner\",\n    model=\"dslim/bert-base-NER\",\n    aggregation_strategy=\"simple\",   # merges B-/I- tokens into spans\n    device=0,                         # GPU 0; set to -1 for CPU\n)\n\ndef extract_entities(text: str) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Return list of {word, entity_group, score, start, end}.\"\"\"\n    return ner(text)\n\ndef build_entity_index(articles: list[dict]) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    articles: list of {id, title, body, published_at}\n    Returns index: entity_text → list of article ids that mention it.\n    \"\"\"\n    index = defaultdict(list)\n    for article in articles:\n        text = article[\"title\"] + \" \" + article[\"body\"]\n        entities = extract_entities(text[:512])   # BERT max 512 tokens\n        for ent in entities:\n            if ent[\"score\"] > 0.85 and ent[\"entity_group\"] in {\"ORG\", \"PER\", \"LOC\"}:\n                key = (ent[\"word\"].strip(), ent[\"entity_group\"])\n                index[key].append(article[\"id\"])\n    return dict(index)\n\n\n# Example usage\narticles = [\n    {\n        \"id\": \"a1\",\n        \"title\": \"Apple acquires AI startup for $500 million\",\n        \"body\": \"Apple Inc. announced on Monday the acquisition of DeepMind rival Imbue, paying approximately $500 million.\",\n        \"published_at\": \"2025-11-01\",\n    },\n    {\n        \"id\": \"a2\",\n        \"title\": \"Tim Cook visits Berlin\",\n        \"body\": \"Apple CEO Tim Cook met with German Chancellor Olaf Scholz in Berlin to discuss supply chain resilience.\",\n        \"published_at\": \"2025-11-02\",\n    },\n]\n\nindex = build_entity_index(articles)\nfor (entity, etype), article_ids in sorted(index.items()):\n    print(f\"{entity:30} [{etype}]  → articles: {article_ids}\")\n\n# Apple Inc.                     [ORG]  → articles: ['a1']\n# Tim Cook                       [PER]  → articles: ['a2']\n# Berlin                         [LOC]  → articles: ['a2']\n"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Best Practices"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Use aggregation_strategy='simple' in Hugging Face pipelines."},{"type":"text","text":" Without it you get raw B-/I- token predictions that need manual span assembly."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Evaluate with seqeval, not sklearn."},{"type":"text","text":" seqeval computes span-level precision/recall/F1 correctly. sklearn accuracy treats each token independently and always over-reports performance."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Fine-tune on 200–500 annotated sentences before concluding the base model is insufficient."},{"type":"text","text":" A small amount of domain-specific data dramatically improves performance on specialised text."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Handle sub-word alignment explicitly."},{"type":"text","text":" When fine-tuning, set labels for non-first sub-tokens to -100 so they do not contribute to the loss."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Score confidence thresholds in production."},{"type":"text","text":" Entities with score < 0.85 are often ambiguous; add a human-review queue for low-confidence spans."}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Performance and Scalability"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"spaCy's "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"en_core_web_sm"},{"type":"text","text":" pipeline processes approximately 50,000 tokens per second on a single CPU core. The transformer-based "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"en_core_web_trf"},{"type":"text","text":" drops to ~2,000–5,000 tokens per second without a GPU but achieves 3–5 F1 points higher on benchmarks. On a modern GPU (A100), the transformer pipeline processes ~100,000 tokens per second with batching, making it viable for real-time news ingestion at the scale of a small news agency."}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Model"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"CoNLL-2003 F1"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Speed (tokens/sec, CPU)"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Best for"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"spaCy en_core_web_sm"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"~84"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"~50,000"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"High-throughput CPU pipelines"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"spaCy en_core_web_trf"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"~90"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"~3,000"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Accuracy-first with GPU"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"dslim/bert-base-NER"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"~91"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"~4,000"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"General purpose Hugging Face"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"GLiNER (span-based)"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"~93"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"~1,500"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Nested entities, zero-shot types"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Security and Reliability"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"NER models trained on general news corpora can produce systematically biased entity assignments: names that appear predominantly in one demographic context get misclassified or missed. For example, some models trained on Western news corpora perform worse on non-Western names and organisations. Before deploying NER in a compliance-sensitive context (legal, medical, financial), audit F1 scores broken out by entity type and demographic group."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Adversarial inputs are a reliability concern: deliberate typos (\"Appl3 Inc.\"), Unicode lookalike characters, or unusual whitespace can fool tokeniser-based models. Rule-based post-processing (a gazetteer of known entities, normalisation of common misspellings) provides a last line of defence. For high-stakes pipelines, add entity confidence scoring and route uncertain spans to human review."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Key Takeaways"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"NER"},{"type":"text","text":" is a token-level classification task that identifies and types spans (people, organisations, locations, dates) in text."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"BIO tagging"},{"type":"text","text":" encodes entity spans as Begin-Inside-Outside labels; a span is correct only when both boundary and type match exactly."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Transformer-based models"},{"type":"text","text":" (BERT, RoBERTa fine-tuned on CoNLL-2003) achieve ~91 F1 and handle contextual disambiguation; spaCy rule-based models trade accuracy for CPU speed."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sub-word tokenisation"},{"type":"text","text":" requires careful label alignment — only the first sub-token of each word should carry the label."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Domain mismatch"},{"type":"text","text":" causes the largest practical F1 drops; fine-tune on 200–500 domain-specific examples before concluding a base model is insufficient."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Evaluate with seqeval"},{"type":"text","text":" at span level — token-level accuracy dramatically over-estimates real performance."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"For nested entities"},{"type":"text","text":" or zero-shot entity types, use span-based models (GLiNER, SpanBERT) rather than BIO sequence labelling."}]}]}]}]}}